title: For Sale:  Winchester 62A
postcontent: Winchester Model 62A Slide (Pump) Action .22 Caliber. Serial # 107140 Manufactured 1944. Compatible and interchangeable with all standard Short, Long and Long Rifle .22 Caliber cartridges. The Model 62 (pre-War & 62A (Post War) Visible Hammer was manufactured from 1932 to 1958. The Model 61 Hammerless from 1932 to 1963. Sadly, but good for collectors, at the end of 1963 Model 61 Production both of these classic Winchester Slide Action rifles had been permanently discontinued when the company went from almost purely handmade firearms to almost completely automated production beginning in 1964. The Winchester Model 62 was a rifle that most men who are my age now owned as a prized possession as teenagers. (Ah, the good old days). When I first acquired this Model 62 I enjoyed shooting it and reliving those good old days a bit but eventually it was cleaned and stored away. This gun is strong in every aspect. It has what I would call a nice light patina of use. Extremely nice but not to the point of a mint example you would not want to shoot. And, it is far, far from just shooter quality. The bluing is outstanding over the entire rifle with only a few barrel freckles and some light scratches on the receiver. The stock is in excellent condition with a few light dings and the butt plate is excellent. Very importantly the action is tight and the bore is superb. The gun is easily 97 percent. Since Winchester discontinued manufacturing their very fine and very popular line of Model 61 Hammerless and Model 62 Exposed Hammer rifles in 1963 values have steadily increased. But they have particularly begun escalating sharply in recent years and no doubt will continue a steady upward march. Any casual or serious Winchester collector cannot go wrong acquiring a Winchester Slide Action .22, especially if it is very good condition and maintained that way. They are a guaranteed quality collectible firearm investment. It is now time for me to pass this one along to another appreciative collector to enjoy and preserve. title: For Sale:  Czechpoint D-Technik VZ 58 Military Classic 7.62x39 Czech Republic
postcontent:
PLEASE NOTE: this is NOT a VZ 2008, which has a US made receiver and US barrel, and which is assembled in the US. This is manufactured in the Czech Republic, with an original Czech made receiver and cold hammer forged chrome-lined barrel. I bought this direct from the importer who brought the rifles over from the Czech Republic, Tennessee Guns International (TGI).

Excellent condition Czech-made VZ 58 rifle. Czechoslovakia was the only Warsaw Pact country that never adopted the AK as their service rifle. When the Soviet Union mandated that all members adopt the 7.62x39mm round as their standard ammunition in 1956, Czechoslovakia designed the VZ 58 to replace the VZ 52 (which fired a 7.62x45mm round that only the Czechs used) as their service rifle.

The VZ 58 has a milled receiver, but weighs a pound less than an AK with a stamped sheet metal receiver. It uses a 30-round aluminum magazine, which is NOT interchangeable with AK magazines. You can order magazines online, and Van's Sporting Goods has a few in stock as well.

This is the more rare Military Classic version. It has hardwood stock, pistol grip and handguards, which only the early VZ 58s used. The Czechs later switched to a reddish colored resin-impregnated wood chip material for the VZ 58's furniture. One magazine is included, and a matching Czech bayonet with hardwood handles is included as well. Please note, the rifle does NOT have a bayonet lug; they were imported from the Czech Republic without one.

Selling for $1,075. Price is firm. Local pickup, cash only. You must show proof of MS residency, and I will complete a bill of sale at the time of sale.
